section.article:
(c) It is shown in a manner acceptable to the Authority that –
The product to be certificated meets the applicable requirements designated in accordance with JAR 21.17;
Any airworthiness provisions not complied with are compensated for by factors that provide an equivalent level of safety;
No feature or characteristic makes it unsafe for the uses for which certification is requested; and
The Type Certificate holder is prepared to comply with JAR 21.44.

(a) The Type Design consists of
The drawings and specifications, and a listing of those drawings and specifications, necessary to define the configuration and the design features of the product shown to comply with the Applicable Requirements;
Information on materials and processes and on methods of manufacture and assembly of the product necessary to ensure the conformity of the product;
The Airworthiness Limitations section of the Instructions for Continued Airworthiness as required by the applicable requirement; and
Any other data necessary to allow by comparison, the determination of the airworthiness of later products of the same type.

(a) A description of the change identifying –
All parts of the Type Design and the approved Manuals affected by the change, and;
The requirements with which the change has been designed to comply in accordance with JAR 21.101.

(a) An applicant for approval of a major change must
Submit to the Authority substantiating data together with any necessary descriptive data for inclusion in the Type Design;
Show that the changed product complies with applicable requirements, as specified in JAR 21.101;
Declare that he has shown compliance with applicable requirements and must provide to the Authority the basis on which such a declaration is made; and

(c) Determine that the design of
Products, or changes [or repairs] thereof, as applicable, comply with applicable requirements and have no unsafe feature;
(Reserved.)

(c) It is shown that:
the product to be certificated meets the applicable requirements designated in accordance with JAR 21N17. (See ACJ 21N21 (c));
any airworthiness provisions not complied with are compensated for by factors that provide an equivalent level of safety;
no feature or characteristic makes the product unsafe for the uses for which certification is requested;
the Type Certificate holder is prepared to comply with JAR 21N44; and
there are provisions to support the continuing airworthiness of the product, and, for aircraft, these are in accordance with ICAO Annex 8, Part 2; and

(a) The Type Design consists of:
The drawings and specifications, and a listing of those drawings and specifications, necessary to define the configuration and the design features of the product shown to comply with the Applicable Requirements;
Information on materials and processes and on methods of manufacture and assembly of the product necessary to ensure the conformity of the product;
The Airworthiness Limitations section of the Instructions for Continued Airworthiness as required by the [applicable requirement]; and
Any other data necessary to allow by comparison, the determination of the airworthiness of later products of the same type.

(c) Before tests under sub-paragraph (a) are undertaken, each applicant must have made all inspections and ground and flight tests necessary to determine:
that the design complies with the airworthiness requirements relevant to the tests performed;
for the test specimen:
that materials and products adequately conform to the specifications in the Type Design;
that parts of the products adequately conform to the drawings in the Type Design; and
that the manufacturing processes, construction and assembly adequately conform to those specified in the Type Design.

(a) A description of the change identifying:
all parts of the Type Design and the approved Manuals affected by the change, and;
the requirements with which the change has been designed to comply, in accordance with JAR 21N101.

(a) An applicant for approval of a major change to a Type Design must:
furnish to the JAA the necessary descriptive data as required by the JAA for inclusion in the Type Design;
Show that the changed product complies with applicable requirements, as specified in JAR 21N101;
Except where the Arrangement set up in accordance with JAR 21N5 provides otherwise, submit to the JAA substantiating data, together with the means by which compliance is shown; and
Comply with JAR 21N33 and, where applicable, 21N35.

(a) to an imported new aircraft if:
documentation required by JAR 21N174 (a) has been submitted, and
it is shown that the aircraft has been produced so as to comply with JAR 21N131;

(a) This Sub-Subpart prescribes:
Procedural requirements for the issue of Joint Technical Standard Order Authorisations to a non-JAA manufacturer;
Rules governing the holders of these Joint Technical Standard Order Authorisations.

(b) Each manufacturer of an article for which he holds a JTSO Authorisation issued under this Subpart N shall permanently and legibly mark each article with the following information:
the name and address of the manufacturer;
the name, type, part number or model designation of the article;
the serial number or the date of manufacture of the article or both; and
the applicable JTSO number.

(b) Each manufacturer of an article for which he holds a JTSO Authorisation issued under this JAR-21 shall permanently and legibly mark each article with the following information:
The name and address of the manufacturer;
The name, type, part number or model designation of the article;
The serial number or the date of manufacture of the article or both; and
The applicable JTSO number.

